
📘 Spring Data JPA – Foundation (SCN)

📌 Concept
🔹 Database
A place to store structured data
Example: MySQL, PostgreSQL

🔹 JDBC (Java Database Connectivity)
Low-level API to interact with DB
You write:
SQL queries
Connection handling
Result parsing
👉 Problem:
Boilerplate code ❌
Manual mapping ❌

🔹 ORM (Object Relational Mapping)
Converts:
Java Object ↔ Database Table
👉 Example:
Employee obj  ↔  employee table

👉 Removes need to manually write SQL for basic operations

🔹 JPA (Java Persistence API)
Specification (interface) for ORM
Defines:
How ORM should work
Rules & annotations
👉 Important:
JPA is NOT implementation

🔹 Hibernate
Implementation of JPA
Actually does the work:
Converts objects → SQL
Executes queries
Manages caching, transactions
👉 So:
JPA = Rules
Hibernate = Implementation


🔹 Spring Data JPA
Abstraction on top of JPA (Hibernate)
👉 Removes:
Boilerplate code
Manual DAO implementation
👉 You just write:
interface EmployeeRepo extends JpaRepository<Employee, Integer> {}


⚙️ Flow (Very Important 🔥)

🔄 Full Flow
Your Code
   ↓
Spring Data JPA
   ↓
JPA (Specification)
   ↓
Hibernate (Implementation)
   ↓
JDBC
   ↓
Database


🧠 What Each Layer Does

1️⃣ Your Code (Service/Controller)
Calls repository methods
repo.save(employee);


2️⃣ Spring Data JPA
Provides ready-made methods:
save()
findById()
delete()
👉 No implementation needed

3️⃣ JPA
Defines rules:
@Entity
@Id
@Table

4️⃣ Hibernate
Converts:
employee object → SQL query

👉 Example:
INSERT INTO employee VALUES(...)


5️⃣ JDBC
Sends SQL to database
Gets result back

6️⃣ Database
Executes query
Returns data

🔁 End-to-End Example Flow
repo.save(emp);

👉 Internally:
Spring Data JPA receives call
Uses Hibernate
Hibernate generates SQL
JDBC executes SQL
DB stores data
Response flows back

🔥 Key Points (Interview)
JDBC = low-level API
ORM = Object ↔ Table mapping
JPA = specification
Hibernate = implementation of JPA
Spring Data JPA = abstraction over JPA
👉 Most Important Line:
“Spring Data JPA uses Hibernate internally, which uses JDBC to interact with the database.”

🧠 Learnings
You never directly use JDBC in Spring Boot (normally)
Hibernate handles SQL generation
Spring Data JPA removes boilerplate DAO code
Flow understanding = Top interview question

⚠️ Reality Check (Important)
If you think:
“Spring Data JPA means no SQL at all”
That’s wrong ❌
For complex queries → you still write SQL / JPQL






📘 Spring Data JPA – Configuration (SCN)

📌 Concept
Spring Boot auto-configures JPA, but we must provide:
DB connection details
JPA behavior settings

⚙️ 5 Important Properties (Must Know 🔥)

1️⃣ Database URL
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/test

👉 Meaning:
Tells Spring:
Which database to connect
DB type = MySQL
Port = 3306
DB name = test

2️⃣ Username
spring.datasource.username=root

👉 Meaning:
Database login username

3️⃣ Password
spring.datasource.password=your_password

👉 Meaning:
Database login password

4️⃣ Hibernate DDL Auto
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update

👉 Meaning:
Controls table creation
Value
Use
create
Drop & create table every time
update
Update existing table ✅
validate
Check schema only
none
Do nothing


5️⃣ Show SQL
spring.jpa.show-sql=true

👉 Meaning:
Shows generated SQL queries in console
Useful for debugging
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true 
👉 Meaning:
Formats SQL into multiple lines
Improves readability

🧠 Optional (But Important)
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.dialect=org.hibernate.dialect.MySQLDialect

👉 Meaning:
Tells Hibernate which SQL syntax to use

🔥 Key Points (Interview)
URL = DB location
Username/Password = authentication
ddl-auto = schema control
show-sql = debugging
Hibernate auto-generates SQL

🧠 Learnings
Minimum config = 3 (URL, username, password)
Most asked = ddl-auto behavior
update is safest for development
Never use create in production ❌


📘 SQL Initialization Properties (SCN)

📌 Concept
Controls when and how data.sql runs in Spring Boot

⚙️ Properties

🔹 1. spring.jpa.defer-datasource-initialization=true
👉 Ensures correct order:
Hibernate creates tables → THEN data.sql runs

✔️ Prevents “table not found” error

🔹 2. spring.sql.init.mode=always
👉 Forces execution of data.sql on startup
✔️ Runs every time app starts
❌ Without this → may not execute

🔹 3. spring.sql.init.data-locations=classpath:data.sql
👉 Tells Spring:
Where your SQL file is located

✔️ Default = src/main/resources/data.sql

🔄 Flow
App Start
   ↓
Tables created (Hibernate)
   ↓
data.sql executed
   ↓
Data inserted


🔥 Key Points
defer → fixes execution order
mode=always → ensures execution
data-locations → file path config

🧠 Learnings
Use all 3 together for smooth setup
Most startup SQL errors come from wrong order
Default location usually doesn’t need config



📘 Spring Data JPA – Annotations (SCN)

📌 Concept
Annotations define:
How Java class maps to DB
How fields behave
Two types here:
JPA annotations → DB mapping
Lombok annotations → reduce boilerplate

🧩 Annotations Breakdown

🔹 1. @Entity
📌 Concept
Marks class as DB table
📌 Example
@Entity
class Employee {}

👉 Without this → JPA will ignore class ❌

🔹 2. @Table
📌 Concept
Specifies table name
@Table(name = "employees")

👉 If not used:
Table name = class name

🔹 3. @Id
📌 Concept
Marks Primary Key
@Id
private int id;

👉 Mandatory for every entity

🔹 4. @GeneratedValue
📌 Concept
Auto-generates ID
@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)

📌 Types
Strategy
Meaning
IDENTITY
Auto-increment (MySQL) ✅
AUTO
Default
SEQUENCE
Uses DB sequence
TABLE
Uses separate table


🔹 5. @Column
📌 Concept
Maps field → column
@Column(name = "emp_name", nullable = false)
private String name;

📌 Use
Rename column
Add constraints

🔹 6. @CreationTimestamp
📌 Concept
Auto sets created time
@CreationTimestamp
private LocalDateTime createdAt;

👉 Managed by Hibernate

🔹 7. @Data (Lombok)
📌 Concept
Generates:
Getter
Setter
toString()
equals() & hashCode()
@Data
class Employee {}


🔹 8. @Builder (Lombok)
📌 Concept
Implements Builder Pattern
@Builder
Employee emp = Employee.builder()
        .name("Vipul")
        .build();

👉 Cleaner object creation

💻 Complete Example
import jakarta.persistence.*;
import lombok.*;
import org.hibernate.annotations.CreationTimestamp;
import java.time.LocalDateTime;

@Entity
@Table(name = "employees")
@Data
@Builder
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private int id;

    @Column(name = "emp_name", nullable = false)
    private String name;

    @CreationTimestamp
    private LocalDateTime createdAt;
}


🔥 Key Points (Interview)
@Entity → class becomes table
@Id → mandatory primary key
@GeneratedValue → auto ID generation
@Column → customize column
@CreationTimestamp → auto timestamp
Lombok reduces boilerplate

🧠 Learnings
Always define @Id
Prefer IDENTITY for MySQL
Use Lombok for cleaner code
@Column is optional but useful
Hibernate handles timestamps automatically

⚠️ Reality Check
@Data can be risky in large apps (because of equals/hashCode)
Avoid using it blindly in entities (interview bonus point 🔥)

📘 @Table, @UniqueConstraint, @Index (SCN)

📌 Concept
@Table → defines table name + constraints + indexes

🧩 Your Code
@Table(
    name="product_table",
    uniqueConstraints = {
        @UniqueConstraint(name = "title_price_unique", columnNames = {"title_x","price"})
    },
    indexes = {
        @Index(name="sku_index", columnList = "sku")
    }
)


🔹 1. @Table(name="product_table")
👉 Maps:
Entity → product_table


🔹 2. @UniqueConstraint
👉 Ensures:
(title_x + price) must be unique

❌ Duplicate combination not allowed

🔹 3. @Index
👉 Creates index on:
sku column

✔️ Faster search queries
❌ Slightly slower inserts

🔥 Key Points
@Table → table config
@UniqueConstraint → prevents duplicate data
@Index → improves performance

🧠 Learnings
Use unique for data integrity
Use index for speed
Unique constraint automatically creates index


🧾 Hibernate – Key Features (SCN Format)

1. 🧠 Concept
Hibernate is an ORM (Object Relational Mapping) framework that maps Java objects to database tables and handles DB operations automatically.

2. ⚙️ Core Features
🔹 1. ORM (Object Relational Mapping)
Maps Java class ↔ Table
Maps Object ↔ Row
Removes manual SQL handling

🔹 2. Database Independence (Dialect)
Works with multiple DBs (MySQL, Oracle, etc.)
Uses Dialect to generate DB-specific SQL
Easy DB switching without code change

🔹 3. Automatic Table Creation
Can auto-create/update tables using:
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update



🔹 4. Caching Mechanism
Improves performance by reducing DB hits
Cache Type
Scope
First Level Cache
Session (default)
Second Level Cache
SessionFactory


🔹 5. HQL (Hibernate Query Language)
Object-oriented query language
Uses class names instead of table names
FROM Employee WHERE salary > 50000


🔹 6. Lazy & Eager Loading
Lazy → Load data when needed (default)
Eager → Load immediately

🔹 7. Transaction Management
Ensures ACID properties
Works with JDBC / JTA

🔹 8. CRUD Operations Simplified
No need to write SQL
session.save(obj);
session.get(Employee.class, id);
session.update(obj);
session.delete(obj);


🔹 9. Associations Mapping
Supports relationships:
One-to-One
One-to-Many
Many-to-One
Many-to-Many

🔹 10. Annotation-Based Configuration
Replaces XML config
@Entity
@Table(name="employee")


3. 🚀 Approach (How Hibernate Works)
Create Entity class
Configure DB connection
Use SessionFactory
Perform operations using Session
Commit transaction

4. 💻 Code Example
Session session = sessionFactory.openSession();
Transaction tx = session.beginTransaction();

Employee emp = new Employee();
emp.setName("Vipul");

session.save(emp);

tx.commit();
session.close();


5. 🎯 Key Points
Reduces boilerplate JDBC code
Improves performance using caching
Database independent
Uses HQL instead of SQL
Handles relationships easily

6. 📌 Learnings
Hibernate abstracts DB complexity
Best for large applications with complex relationships
Understanding Session + Cache + Mapping is crucial


